{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01Y91MAeSuVg6Zu4nMoPTXWz","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# TrustManager Controller\n2\t\n3\t## What it reconciles\n4\t\n5\tThe TrustManager controller owns the `TrustManager` cluster-scoped singleton CRD\n6\t(`operator.openshift.io/v1alpha1`). When a `TrustManager` CR named `cluster` exists,\n7\tthe controller ensures that the trust-manager operand Deployment and its full supporting\n8\tresource set are present and match the declared spec.\n9\t\n10\t## Resource watch surface (13+ types)\n11\t\n12\t`SetupWithManager` registers watches for:\n13\t\n14\t| Watch target | Predicate |\n15\t|---|---|\n16\t| `TrustManager` (For) | GenerationChangedPredicate |\n17\t| `ServiceAccount` | managed-label predicate |\n18\t| `Deployment` | managed-label + ignore-status-update |\n19\t| `Service` | managed-label |\n20\t| `ConfigMap` (controller-owned) | managed-label |\n21\t| `ConfigMap` (CNO CA bundle) | namespace==operator-ns AND name==trusted-ca-bundle |\n22\t| `ClusterRole`, `ClusterRoleBinding` | managed-label |\n23\t| `Role`, `RoleBinding` | managed-label |\n24\t| `Certificate`, `Issuer` | managed-label + ignore-status-update |\n25\t| `ValidatingWebhookConfiguration` | managed-label |\n26\t\n27\tThe \"managed-label predicate\" matches `cert-manager.io/managed-by: cert-manager-trust-manager`.\n28\tOn Update events it checks both old and new objects, so removing the label still triggers\n29\treconciliation. The CNO CA bundle ConfigMap is watched unconditionally by name/namespace\n30\tbecause CNO owns it (it carries no managed label).\n31\t\n32\t## Mutation pipeline\n33\t\n34\t`reconcileTrustManagerDeployment` calls `getDeploymentObject`, which applies a sequential\n35\tchain of named mutate functions to a freshly decoded bindata Deployment:\n36\t\n37\t1. `validateDeploymentManifest` — asserts the expected container name and TLS secret volume\n38\t   are present; returns an `IrrecoverableError` if not, preventing further apply.\n39\t2. `common.UpdateName / UpdateNamespace / UpdateResourceLabels` — sets stable identity fields.\n40\t3. `updateResourceAnnotations`, `updatePodTemplateLabels` — propagates user-provided labels\n41\t   and annotations from `spec.controllerConfig`.\n42\t4. `updateDeploymentArgs` — rebuilds the container arg list from spec fields (logLevel,\n43\t   logFormat, trustNamespace, secretTargets, filterExpiredCertificates, defaultCAPackage).\n44\t5. `updateServiceAccountName`, `updateTLSSecretVolume` — wires up the operator-managed SA\n45\t   and the webhook TLS Secret volume.\n46\t6. `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume` — when `DefaultCAPackage.Policy == Enabled`, adds the\n47\t   CNO-injected ConfigMap volume/mount and stamps the pod template with a hash annotation.\n48\t7. `updateImage`, `updateResourceRequirements`, `updateAffinityRules`, `updatePodTolerations`,\n49\t   `updateNodeSelector` — apply user overrides, each validating before mutating.\n50\t\n51\tOnce built, `createOrApplyDeployment` compares against the live object with `deploymentModified`\n52\t(a field-by-field comparison that deliberately excludes API-server-defaulted probe scalars),\n53\tand skips the apply if nothing changed. Writes use Server-Side Apply via\n54\t`client.Patch(..., client.Apply, client.FieldOwner(fieldOwner), client.ForceOwnership)`.\n55\t\n56\t## ConfigMap hash restart\n57\t\n58\t`updateDefaultCAPackageVolume` hashes the content of the CNO CA bundle ConfigMap and sets it\n59\tas a pod template annotation (`cert-manager.io/ca-bundle-hash`). When CNO rotates the bundle,\n60\tthe predicate on the CNO ConfigMap watch fires, reconciliation runs, the hash changes, and\n61\tKubernetes performs a rolling restart of the Deployment — no manual intervention required.\n62\t\n63\t## OptionalInformer wiring\n64\t\n65\tThe TrustManager controller itself uses direct predicate-based watches rather than\n66\t`OptionalInformer`, because trust-manager is deployed exclusively on OpenShift where the\n67\tCNO-managed CA bundle ConfigMap always exists. The `OptionalInformer` pattern (see\n68\t`optional-informer.md`) is used by the sibling certmanager controller for the OpenShift\n69\tInfrastructure API, which is absent on MicroShift. TrustManager avoids the same complexity\n70\tbecause its only OpenShift-specific dependency (the CA bundle ConfigMap) is filtered by a\n71\tplain name/namespace predicate rather than by API discovery.\n72\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"07ea1630-67ed-4715-951f-59d24e018baf","uuid":"d57a4504-0e98-4c7c-a246-418dddd288c9","timestamp":"2026-07-20T16:54:19.210Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/kpais/kpais-workspace/a_b_evals/repos/cert-manager-operator-treatment/agentic/design-docs/components/trustmanager-controller.md","content":"# TrustManager Controller\n\n## What it reconciles\n\nThe TrustManager controller owns the `TrustManager` cluster-scoped singleton CRD\n(`operator.openshift.io/v1alpha1`). When a `TrustManager` CR named `cluster` exists,\nthe controller ensures that the trust-manager operand Deployment and its full supporting\nresource set are present and match the declared spec.\n\n## Resource watch surface (13+ types)\n\n`SetupWithManager` registers watches for:\n\n| Watch target | Predicate |\n|---|---|\n| `TrustManager` (For) | GenerationChangedPredicate |\n| `ServiceAccount` | managed-label predicate |\n| `Deployment` | managed-label + ignore-status-update |\n| `Service` | managed-label |\n| `ConfigMap` (controller-owned) | managed-label |\n| `ConfigMap` (CNO CA bundle) | namespace==operator-ns AND name==trusted-ca-bundle |\n| `ClusterRole`, `ClusterRoleBinding` | managed-label |\n| `Role`, `RoleBinding` | managed-label |\n| `Certificate`, `Issuer` | managed-label + ignore-status-update |\n| `ValidatingWebhookConfiguration` | managed-label |\n\nThe \"managed-label predicate\" matches `cert-manager.io/managed-by: cert-manager-trust-manager`.\nOn Update events it checks both old and new objects, so removing the label still triggers\nreconciliation. The CNO CA bundle ConfigMap is watched unconditionally by name/namespace\nbecause CNO owns it (it carries no managed label).\n\n## Mutation pipeline\n\n`reconcileTrustManagerDeployment` calls `getDeploymentObject`, which applies a sequential\nchain of named mutate functions to a freshly decoded bindata Deployment:\n\n1. `validateDeploymentManifest` — asserts the expected container name and TLS secret volume\n   are present; returns an `IrrecoverableError` if not, preventing further apply.\n2. `common.UpdateName / UpdateNamespace / UpdateResourceLabels` — sets stable identity fields.\n3. `updateResourceAnnotations`, `updatePodTemplateLabels` — propagates user-provided labels\n   and annotations from `spec.controllerConfig`.\n4. `updateDeploymentArgs` — rebuilds the container arg list from spec fields (logLevel,\n   logFormat, trustNamespace, secretTargets, filterExpiredCertificates, defaultCAPackage).\n5. `updateServiceAccountName`, `updateTLSSecretVolume` — wires up the operator-managed SA\n   and the webhook TLS Secret volume.\n6. `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume` — when `DefaultCAPackage.Policy == Enabled`, adds the\n   CNO-injected ConfigMap volume/mount and stamps the pod template with a hash annotation.\n7. `updateImage`, `updateResourceRequirements`, `updateAffinityRules`, `updatePodTolerations`,\n   `updateNodeSelector` — apply user overrides, each validating before mutating.\n\nOnce built, `createOrApplyDeployment` compares against the live object with `deploymentModified`\n(a field-by-field comparison that deliberately excludes API-server-defaulted probe scalars),\nand skips the apply if nothing changed. Writes use Server-Side Apply via\n`client.Patch(..., client.Apply, client.FieldOwner(fieldOwner), client.ForceOwnership)`.\n\n## ConfigMap hash restart\n\n`updateDefaultCAPackageVolume` hashes the content of the CNO CA bundle ConfigMap and sets it\nas a pod template annotation (`cert-manager.io/ca-bundle-hash`). When CNO rotates the bundle,\nthe predicate on the CNO ConfigMap watch fires, reconciliation runs, the hash changes, and\nKubernetes performs a rolling restart of the Deployment — no manual intervention required.\n\n## OptionalInformer wiring\n\nThe TrustManager controller itself uses direct predicate-based watches rather than\n`OptionalInformer`, because trust-manager is deployed exclusively on OpenShift where the\nCNO-managed CA bundle ConfigMap always exists. The `OptionalInformer` pattern (see\n`optional-informer.md`) is used by the sibling certmanager controller for the OpenShift\nInfrastructure API, which is absent on MicroShift. TrustManager avoids the same complexity\nbecause its only OpenShift-specific dependency (the CA bundle ConfigMap) is filtered by a\nplain name/namespace predicate rather than by API discovery.\n","numLines":72,"startLine":1,"totalLines":72}}}
